    {
      "id": "3744106e9e3a9fa708c9e78aa0898d8bc1adae07",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2016-03-15 15:27:41.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\n(1 comment)\n\nThis looks like it might fix the large request buffer leak that is happening every 15 minutes in soak testing.\n\nWhat about the ptlrpc_cache leak that is happening 10x per second?  It isn't reasonable to have 400k of ptlrpc_request structs in the slab cache, and I don't think that could relate to recovery.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "2df34b60f5311c8022cab2de73d033f08f15eab1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 12,
        "name": "wangdi",
        "email": "di.wang@intel.com",
        "username": "wangdi",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2016-03-15 16:17:43.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n\"What about the ptlrpc_cache leak that is happening 10x per second? It isn't reasonable to have 400k of ptlrpc_request structs in the slab cache, and I don't think that could relate to recovery.\"\n\nHmm, according to the debug log, it looks like recovery is blocked on one MDT, then all of recovery on this MDT is blocked on final ping (complete_signal_replay()), so every clients (include clients and all other MDTs) keep resend the new final ping every 5 seconds, which will be queued on the failover MDT. then cause OOM here.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "a461abe1dc00c1b962779d24533c96b59c189c78",
      "author": {
